{
 "_name": "s27_cross_layer_mobiles",
 "_desc": "FUTURE-PROTOCOL scenario (spec 2026-07-17-cross-layer-mobile-first-contact-design.md) — PARTIALLY RED until slices S1-S4 land; then joins BASELINE.md as mandatory. Two static layers, leaf 4 {S1..S4 = ids 101..104} + leaf 7 {T1..T4 = ids 111..114}, bridged by dual-layer gateway G1 (id 10, windows). Four REAL-CRYPTO mobiles (seed-derived key_hash32): M1@S1 0x2716EFCD, M2@S4 0x3A3E77A3, M3@T1 0xBCC13CC5, M4@T4 0x455FCF59. M1 knows only (layer,hash) addresses. ⚠ Static ids are HIGH (101+) DELIBERATELY: hosted-mobile local ids allocate from 17.. and a cold-boot allocation can alias a static id, poisoning rt_skip_mobile_transit at the home (defer-loop, no delivery) — a REAL pre-existing bug found by this scenario's first dry run (2026-07-17, see the spec's findings note); it needs its own fix+test, not this scenario. Spare late-start homes S5=105/T5=115/T6=116 (start_at_ms 560000) keep the INITIAL home picks deterministic (exactly one host in range per mobile at registration) and provide unambiguous re-home targets. PHASES: (A) register (homes 101/104/111/114); (B) PLAINTEXT-FIRST with INTRO auto-pubkey-attach (spec S2/D1): M1->M2 same-layer, M1->M3 + M1->M4 cross-layer via the DELEGATED send_layer (spec S1; the EXISTING layer-path format, frame_codec.h:519); replies attach keys back — NO WANT_PUBKEY flood anywhere; (C) ENCRYPTED both directions incl. CROSS-LAYER sealed (spec S4); (D) 3-of-4 RE-HOME: S4/T1/T4 die (dies_at_ms 600k/620k/640k) -> M2->S5(105), M3->T5(115), M4->T6(116); M1's home S1 SURVIVES = stable sender anchor; (E) ENCRYPTED again post-re-home (stale home caches re-resolve; re-pushed keys serve at the NEW homes — spec S3). ⚠ SIM-REPO PREREQ: the EXISTING wrapper verb `send_layer <l1,l2,..> <hash-decimal> <body>` (s09/s16) is reused for plaintext XL (S1 makes it legal FROM a mobile via delegation); ONE new wrapper verb `send_layerx <l1,l2,..> <hash-decimal> <body>` is needed for the sealed variant (mirrors send_hash/send_hashx). NOTE the wrapper's send_layer takes DECIMAL hashes (send_hash takes hex) - each verb keeps its own convention. Assertions use ONLY existing emit names (mobile_adopted / peer_key_cached / push). ⚠ TODAY-STATE (pre-slices, dry-runs 2026-07-17/18): ~12-13 of 30 asserts green = the today-protocol subset (4+1 initial adopts, hello-m2/re-m2 same-layer, 3 death-driven re-homes, M5's initial adopt + hello-m5-moved via the stale proxy); the cross-layer plaintext trio (hello-m3/re-m3/re-m4) is ACCIDENTALLY green-ish — today's mobile send_layer originates on the static plane with a local-id origin (the S1 plane-leak) and is TIMING-FRAGILE (adding M5 flipped re-m4 red with zero functional change). Do NOT chase flips within that trio; they become deterministic under S1's delegation. PHASE F (proactive re-home, spec FSM S6.4-C): M5 (fake hash 0x44070031, plaintext-only) registers to S3 over a DELIBERATELY WEAK link (snr 14 -> quality tier weak -> T=min + pre-scan); strong spare home SX (id 106, snr 55 to M5) starts at 800k with BOTH homes alive -> sustained-better + rehome-dwell -> VOLUNTARY re-home S3(103)->SX(106) -> the NEW home notifies the OLD (breadcrumb-9, D10) -> S1's send_hash to M5 at 1150k must deliver THROUGH the redirect chain (zero-blackhole handoff; this last assert is GREEN today via S3's static proxy and MUST STAY green across the F implementation).",
